<subSubSection id="C353655E69777A20DDA82AC90656FDB8" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BF636D569777A20DDA82AC90656FDB8" blockId="3.[163,1071,402,541]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">
Comment: Since this species was previously known only from the environs of Pokhara, it was assumed to be endemic to the Annapurna range (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD84B2469777A20DE8D2AF4016BFE61" author="ASSING V" box="[902,1059,431,453]" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" pagination="115 - 190" refId="ref11068" refString="ASSING V. (2012 a): The Rugilus species of the Palaearctic and Oriental regions (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Stuttgarter Beitrage zur Naturkunde A, Neue Serie 5: 115 - 190." type="journal article" year="2012">ASSING 2012a</bibRefCitation>
). However, the above record and the discovery of two similar micropterous species in the Annapurna range suggest that 
<taxonomicName id="4C494D5669777A20DCEF2AB107D5FE5B" baseAuthorityName="COIFFAIT" baseAuthorityYear="1975" box="[484,669,490,511]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rugilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="174" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadridentatus">
<emphasis id="B93DEAC769777A20DCEF2AB107D5FE5B" box="[484,669,490,511]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">R. quadridentatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is actually endemic to the 
<collectingRegion id="498DF83769777A20DEC92AB205AFFDB9" country="Nepal" name="Dhawalagiri" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Dhaulagiri region</collectingRegion>
. The distinctive male sternite VII is illustrated in 
<figureCitation id="13722A5069777A20DFD6295C0652FDB8" box="[733,794,519,541]" captionStart="Figs 1-7" captionStartId="4.[163,203,1098,1118]" captionTargetBox="[171,1067,199,1075]" captionTargetId="figure-251@4.[162,1069,197,1082]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1-7: Rugilus rectus nov.sp. (1-6) and R. quadridentatus (COIFFAIT) (7): (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3, 7) male sternite VII; (4) male sternite VIII; (5) aedeagus in lateral view; (6) ventral process of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-2: 1.0 mm; 3-7: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4507309" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4507309/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="174">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
